# Project Context
Building a physician persona simulation for a research engineering 
take-home assignment. 100 real US physician personas from Medicare 
claims data, validated against actual prescribing behavior.

# Git Discipline
- Commit after every meaningful unit of work
- Commit messages: short, descriptive imperative or sentence-style titles
  (e.g. "Require Part D 2023 rows in tirzepatide cohort script"); no "phase X.Y" prefix
- Never commit data/raw/ or data/processed/ (gitignored)
- Always commit data/output/ files (personas, ground truth — these 
  are small JSONs that define the experiment)
- Commit scripts BEFORE running them, then commit results AFTER 
  reviewing output
- If a script changes, commit the change before re-running

# Code Style
- Python 3.11+
- Type hints on all function signatures
- Docstrings on all public functions
- No classes unless genuinely needed — prefer functions and dicts
- pandas for data, no spark/dask
- All file paths relative to project root
- Print progress for any operation taking >10 seconds

# Data Handling
- CMS CSV files are multi-GB. ALWAYS use chunked reading.
- NPI columns must be cast to string (they have leading zeros).
- All joins on NPI: cast both sides to str and strip whitespace first.
- CMS files may use latin-1 encoding, not UTF-8. Try both.

# API Calls
- Together AI for LLM inference (OpenAI-compatible API)
- Use async where possible with concurrency semaphore
- Always implement retry logic with exponential backoff
- Cache responses to avoid re-running on restart
